	(222, 0, 16, 'Calling for Developers for Joomla! Certification Program', 'calling-for-developers-for-joomla-certification-pr', '<p>The Certification Platform Team is responsible to create and maintain the certification platform which consist of Exam Delivery, Learning Partners Dashboard, Payments, Enrollment and maintaining directory of Certified Users.</p>\r\n<p>The Joomla Certification program is about to launch in few weeks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Currently we seek for new developers with the following skills to join our team to improve the platform and code new segments;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>PHP MySQL, MVC Programming / Backend Developer OR</li>\r\n<li>HTML CSS JS / Frontend Developer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Potential volunteers, please apply using this form;</p>\r\n<p>https://certification.joomla.org/contribute/volunteer</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 1, 0, 0, 813, '2016-04-28 09:50:57', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
	(223, 0, 60, 'Current State of Joomla!X', 'current-state-of-joomlax', '<p>The current development of Joomla! X (currently, X == 4) happens in the <a href="https://github.com/joomla-projects/joomla-pythagoras">Pythagoras repository on GitHub</a>.</p>\r\n<p>We tried an incremental approach, i.e., to transform J!3 into J!4 using small steps building upon the J!3 code base, as we decided on the second Architecture Sprint in Athens (Greece). The tight coupling and insufficient test coverage, however, makes it extremely hard to apply the state-of-the-art architecture, which was decided on during the first Architecture Sprint in Odense (Denmark) -- hard from a technical and even more from a management and effort point of view. Experience showed that this would take two to three times the effort as compared to a ground up approach.</p>\r\n<p>So it was just consequent, that in discussing this within the group it was suggested to start from a fresh ground, a clean base, to create the basic architecture, and to port existing functionality in subsequent steps. Instead of building around existing functionalities, we would add existing functionality and libraries, both framework and external, to the clean base, one after one, staying true to previously made intentions. Additionaly we would follow the J!3.x releases and re-use concepts and code from there.</p>\r\n<p>The J!4 Architecture Team decided to try this approach. The prioirity remains to have a on click upgrade for core and minimal backwards compatibility breaks for existing extensions,&nbsp; yet opening up new ways to do things for those who wish to try them.</p>\r\n<p>It took some time for this approach to come to fruition, to get the clean base to a presentable embryonic stage. Last week, it has left the playground mode, and the <a href="https://github.com/joomla-projects/joomla-pythagoras/tree/clean-base">clean-base branch</a> was updated with the recent developments.</p>\r\n<p>Since then, work on the Doctrine storage handler has started, which will allow Joomla!X to really support a wide range of database systems. We are now working publically to what we have named the <a href="https://github.com/joomla-projects/joomla-pythagoras/blob/clean-base/README.md">"Chris Davenport Happy Milestone" (CDHM)</a>. The CDHM milestone is intended to showcase and prove the architectural concepts.<br />The next tasks are to add a first horizontal component, handling the state (publish, unpublish, archive, trash, publish_up, and publish_down), and API and CLI access.</p>\r\n<p>It is a goal of the Architecture Group to be able to show the concepts of Joomla!X with <em>running code</em> at the J and Beyond conference in Barcelona (Spain) later in May this year.</p>\r\n<p>Prior to the conference on Thursday afternoon there will be an informal gathering to demonstrate and explain the state of work (details will follow).</p>\r\n<p>After the conference, the Architecture Team will start to cleanup the repository and reduce the number of branches. Issues and pull requests, that target at the 3.x version will be moved to the current CMS repository.</p>\r\n<p>The Joomla! 4 Architecture Team</p>', NULL, 1, 0, 0, 625, '2016-04-28 00:00:00', 625, '2016-04-28 23:02:11', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
	(224, 0, 44, 'JED Team Meeting Notes - 28th April 2016', 'jed-team-meeting-notes-28th-april-2016', '<p>Today the Joomla Extensions Directory (JED) team met at 2pm GMT via Glip to discuss our progress of current tasks.</p>\r\n<p>In attendance: Matthew Baylor, Jaz Parkyn, Luca Marzo, Mark Smeed, Paul Franklin, Hugh Douglas-Smith, Claire Mandville</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Statistics for the month of April 2016</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Extensions: 145 Approved, 14 Pending</li>\r\n<li>Tickets: 194 Processed, 29 Pending</li>\r\n<li>Reviews: 704 Submitted</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Changes to Team Structure</strong></p>\r\n<p>Tessa is stepping back from some of her JED duties due to her schedule, and as such, Jaz has stepped up to take the Assistant Team Manager role, and Luca has stepped up to take the Listing Team Manager role.</p>\r\n<p>Matt and Jaz will be interviewing people who recently submitted volunteer applications; we hope to add new members to the team shortly and will get them trained up to start processing listings and tickets as soon as possible.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>J and Beyond</strong></p>\r\n<p>Quite a few members of the JED Team will be attending the J and Beyond conference in Barcelona on 20th - 22nd May - if you see us, come and say hello!</p>\r\n<p>We are also proud to have some sessions being presented by members of the JED Team:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Aleksander Kuczek - &ldquo;Better Safe Than Sorry. Updating Joomla keeps hackers away.&rdquo;<br /><a href="http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=119&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s">http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=119&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s</a></li>\r\n<li>Hugh Douglas-Smith - &ldquo;e-Commerce, the customer journey and why people don\'t buy&rdquo;<br /><a href="http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=164&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s">http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=164&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s</a></li>\r\n<li>Rob Clayburn - &ldquo;Javascript - why can\'t we all just get along?&rdquo;<br /><a href="http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=286&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s">http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=286&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s</a></li>\r\n<li>Anibal Sanchez - &ldquo;JED development: how to collaborate and improve our extensions directory&rdquo;<br /><a href="http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=305&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s">http://jandbeyond.org/programme.html?view=session&amp;id=305&amp;return=L3Byb2dyYW1tZS5odG1s</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Contributing to JED</strong></p>\r\n<p>We are currently ironing out a few issues with the development environment and will provide updates on this as soon as possible.</p>\r\n<p>If you find any bugs or would like to suggest an improvement, please find the issue on our JIRA Issue Tracker. Your opinion could make a significant impact on the Extensions Directory.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The next JED team meeting will take place on 27th May 2016 at the same time.</p>', NULL, 1, 0, 0, 695, '2016-04-28 14:04:22', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
